INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("115", "1", "2018-03-15 21:40:31", "2018-03-15 21:40:31", "Alright then, after giving it much thought you have decided and are hell-bent on becoming the next “Batman” of Web Development. You want to be that “Badass Code Monkey” that sips on their coffee and just spits out poems when writing code, and your web pages look like they were painted by Leonardo Da Vinci himself.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBut…………………………! Yeah, there is a huge but here.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you are anything like me and unlike the people who seem to have it all figured out, you are pretty lost and don’t even know where to begin.\r\n\r\nIn that case, let me take this opportunity to clear up a few things for you to help you get started on your path to become the next “Web Developer Baddy”.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>What\'s my story??</b><strong> </strong></h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSince you made it past the introduction I am going to take a hint that you have a plethora of questions on how to become a Web Developer and the bigger question, Why the hell should you even consider taking advice from me, a random guy on a random blog”.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWell, to answer your bigger question first let me give you a little back-story about myself.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI am your average Web Developer with a glorified bachelor’s Degree in Software Engineering and decent GPA of 3.26/4 from Michigan Technological University, which was on the 2017 Forbes list of top 25 STEM colleges in the United States.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<pre><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-114 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/graduation-1-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow, you might be thinking, damn! This guy went to college for 4 years and got trained to become a Software Engineer. He must know what the hell he is talking about.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLet me stop your train of thoughts right there and tell you that even after graduating with a bachelor’s in Software Engineering and knowing that I wanted to become a Web Developer, I had no clue where to start looking for a job or even what kind of Developer I wanted to be.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn my Senior Design courses, I had led the Front-End Development of two Web-Applications on a team of 6 Software Developers in a production environment. (You can check out the Web-Apps on my portfolio at <a href=\"http://prakhar-keshari.com/\">http://prakhar -keshari.com</a>). Hell, I had even led one of the projects as a lead and Scrum Master. If you don’t know what a Scrum Master is don’t worry about it. Just think of it as a Pirate Captain who yells at their crew of Pirates(Developers) and gives them chores to keep the ship running (Software Development Process).\r\n\r\nTo cut the long story short, I had gotten exposed to the idea of Web Development and had spent time learning and applying the core web technologies like HTML5, CSS3, and JavaScript on the front-end, and still had no idea what kind of Developer I wanted to be. If you don’t know what these technologies are, or what front-end is I will explain them later in this post.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOnce I was close to graduation and started job hunting, it hit me pretty quickly that I did not know a whole lot of what a real-world Web Developer is like. In my mind, I knew I would be creating web pages and making them look pretty with CSS and JavaScript, but of course, it couldn’t be just that. Soon, I started running into a sea of different technologies, frameworks and software tools that were being demanded as required qualifications on every job-post I ran into. My frustration kept rising and the overwhelm was peaking thinking about how little I knew about Web Development even after going to college for 4 years.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhy am I telling you all this?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe main reason being, I want to tell you that it is ok to not know everything and feel confused and lost. This is the fun part of figuring things out. Would you really appreciate anything if it was just handed to you without even a little challenge? I can’t, and that is when I decided to roll up my sleeves, pull up socks and dive into the web and find me some answers.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLet me share with you my findings….\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><strong>The first thing you need to understand is what makes a web application and what kind of developers are doing all the magic</strong><strong> </strong></h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3><strong>Them Stacks ………..</strong></h3>\r\n<pre><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-93 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/web-stack.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"700\" height=\"399\" /></pre>\r\nThe Web Development is primarily divided into 2 stacks. In case you were wondering, Web stack is a collection of software required for Web Development. There is a Front-End stack that is all the code responsible for all the client-side interactions that you experience on your browser; and a Back-End stack that is collection of database(s) containing the data and server-side software programs that serve the data to the client-side programs which then populate that data with on our browser window. Now, this gives us three kinds of Developers, Front-End, Back-End and a Full-Stack Web Developer.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><strong>Front-End Web Developer</strong></h2>\r\n<pre><strong><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-101 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/front-end.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"618\" height=\"393\" /> </strong></pre>\r\nYou might have surfed the Web for years with awe and admiration looking at the beautiful layouts of the web pages, cool animations, and seamless functionality. But, did you ever take a moment and wonder who is responsible for such crafts-men ship?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is where our artist, the Front-Developer comes in.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Front-End Developer whips out his paintbrush, and uses a multitude of tools, programming languages and frameworks on his color-palette and breathes life into the web-pages. The core technologies are …\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHTML5 (Markup Language) to create and layout the content on a web page,\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCSS3 (Styling Language) to give the content some color, taste, and personality, and\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nJavaScript (Programming Language) to make the animations and the seamless functionality that you (the user) gets to experience when doing things like making a video play with just a click, or make a picture zoom out when hovering over it, etc.…..\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThese are all the languages that a Front-End Developer uses to develop software that runs on your browser and creates everything you see on your screen.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are all sorts of other libraries/frameworks like JQuery, Angular, React and a hundred others, but I will be covering those in the following posts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><strong>Back-End Web Developer</strong></h2>\r\n<pre><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-103 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/back-end.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"490\" height=\"340\" /></pre>\r\nNow if a Front-End Developer is our artist in the front, a Back-End Developer is our mastermind-architect in the back; he is responsible for creating the utility under the hood by writing server-side programs that the user doesn’t see.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHis tool-kit contains a combination of tools like databases, which is a collection of rows and tables containing the data.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis data then gets picked up by software developed with server-side programming languages like PHP, Ruby, Python, JavaScript, etc.,\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe data then gets served to the client-side software developed by our artist, the Front-End Developer, which is then displayed on the browser with beautiful animations and layouts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI will be going in depth about back-end technologies in the future posts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><strong>Full-Stack Web Developer</strong></h2>\r\n<pre><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-104 size-large\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/full-stack-1024x670.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"525\" height=\"344\" /></pre>\r\nA Full-Stack Developer is our “Jack of All Trades”, whose knowledge and skills are not just limited to the front-end or the back-end but the whole stack.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis makes our Full-Stack Developer both the artist and the mastermind-architect that can create the magic in the front-end while developing the utility in the back-end.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><strong>Where to go after this?</strong></h2>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\nAfter researching and comparing the career-path of the three types of Developers I am going to say it is entirely going to come down to your interests and what you might enjoy more.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou probably have heard this from a hundred other people and I am going to reiterate it, pick what you think seems interesting to you, and then go to work and learn the technologies around that sphere of development.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is just a glimpse of a bigger picture that I have shown you. Web Development is a beast in itself with an ever-changing ecosystem of tools, languages, and frameworks both in the front-end and the back-end.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLearning Web Development is a time-consuming process that is going to take some real effort and patience if you truly want to master your craft.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo, I am going to suggest that you do more research and find out for yourself on which side of stack you see yourself.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnd if you are like me that wants the best of both worlds and enjoy the artistic side of the front-end development while being equipped to plan the back-end domination.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nStart with the front or the back, pick one and while you get better at one, spend time learning the other and slowly watch yourself become the “Full-Stack Ninja”.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><strong>Resources to get you started </strong></h2>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Paid Courses</b>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.lynda.com\">https://www.lynda.com</a><strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://teamtreehouse.com\">https://teamtreehouse.com</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Free Courses</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.freecodecamp.org\">www.freecodecamp.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3><strong>Helpful blogs</strong></h3>\r\n<a href=\"https://medium.com\">https://medium.com</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://css-tricks.com/\">https://css-tricks.com/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3><strong>For all your head-scratching questions and issues</strong></h3>\r\n<a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com\">https://stackoverflow.com</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3><strong>YouTube Channels for motivation, tutorials, and advice</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>\r\n<h4><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCyUBW72KU30dfAYWLVNZO8Q\">Stefan Mischook</a></h4>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThis guy is your wise monk in the land of Web Development\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>\r\n<h4><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/user/jsonmez\">John Sonmez</a></h4>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf you want to learn about soft skills to thrive in Web Development industry, this is your guy.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>\r\n<h4><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/user/TechGuyWeb\">Traversy Media</a></h4>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFront to Back! this guy has got you covered with an elaborate playlist of focused tutorial courses. He himself is a self-taught developer and I highly respect him for talking about his own struggles in life while running a successful freelance career.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>\r\n<h4><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC46wWUso9H5KPQcoL9iE3Ug\">Coding Phase</a></h4>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThis guy not only provides helpful tutorial videos but also shows how to start from nothing and become a successful Front-End Developer.", "What you need to know before you even think about becoming a Web Developer", "Alright then, after giving it much thought you have decided and are hell bent on becoming the next “Batman” of Web Development. ", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "74-revision-v1", "", "", "2018-03-15 21:40:31", "2018-03-15 21:40:31", "", "74", "http://localhost:8888/2018/03/15/74-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
